Over-the-top: Excessively flamboyant or outrageous. Their wedding was over-the-top and cost a fortune! #Idiom #ESL RT http://t.co/88oFRljAU9
Sunday night blues: The anxiety/depression experienced toward the end of the weekend knowing work/school starts soon. http://t.co/d2m3CajDJp
@cr_mari_lu Thanks for the response! Keep the replies and retweets going. And, don't worry, a lifelong love is hard to find. :D
The love of your life: The person you love most in all your life. Have you met the love of your life yet? #Idiom #ESL http://t.co/h9Z30ZfxZP
Party like it's 1999: To celebrate in a wild, crazy way. #Twitter, party like it's 1999 this weekend! #Prince #Idiom http://t.co/49vLeCHx3p
@_twit_or_tweet this last idiom was for you. Thanks for the motivation.
Method to/in one's madness: A purpose to/in what one is doing, though it may seem crazy. #Idiom #English #ESL http://t.co/pBeZ1e3k3t
Back (someone) up (Phrasal Verb): Support. My parents backed me up when I decided to go abroad to study. #Idiom #ESL http://t.co/AiLEqTAQ9L
Let sleeping dogs lie: Leave something alone if it might cause trouble. Why mention the fight? Let sleeping dogs lie. http://t.co/lDArA4uTtX
Wicked: Really, very (New England, USA #slang to add emphasis). The Red Sox played a wicked good game last night. RT http://t.co/ywaj4dQy8r
Sick (#slang): Great, amazing, "cool," "awesome." Aston Martin makes some sick cars! #Idiom #English #ESL Rt me. http://t.co/vGfzX6wRww
Make a fool of yourself: To do something that makes you seem stupid. She made a fool of herself when she was drunk. http://t.co/39ses9GN6P
Pain in the neck: A difficult or annoying thing or person. My ex-boyfriend is a real pain in the neck. #Idiom #ESL http://t.co/gUa6viYTKh
Beauty sleep: The sleep one requires to feel healthy/look attractive "I need my beauty sleep" is often said jokingly. http://t.co/F4HRDUnbq7
Kick the bucket: An impolite way to say someone has died. My sister's bird kicked the bucket when she went on holiday http://t.co/6osotQkg7f
Have good vibes (#slang): To feel good/positive about sth. I have good vibes about the upcoming weekend. #Idiom #ESL http://t.co/AkRQJOdigX
A taste of own medicine: Sarah is angry that Bill insulted her, but she's always rude to him. I guess she got a taste of her own medicine.
A taste of one's own medicine: A sample of the unpleasantness that one has caused others. #Idiom #English #ESL RT me http://t.co/KzJePOuWBk
Blow off (#slang): To avoid or neglect a responsibility. We should blow off work and go to the cinema. #Idiom #ESL RT http://t.co/DnUzR2nZbT
Hold your horses: Stop; Slow down; Reconsider. Joe, hold your horses! You're speaking too fast and I can't follow. RT http://t.co/DQj8juVBKT
Blow over (Phrasal verb): To subside or diminish. He's angry about the fight but it'll blow over soon. #Idiom #ESL RT http://t.co/whKeIa3mNM
Couch potato: A lazy person, often addicted to TV & junk food. Carlos watched TV all weekend. What a couch potato! RT http://t.co/JZfJonqHsC
Chill out (#slang): To calm down; Relax. After work tonight, we're going to chill out and watch a movie. #Idiom #ESL http://t.co/3FG3uFqfqz
Miss the boat: To miss out on something. I missed the boat to register for chemistry when I forgot the deadline. #ESL http://t.co/8pIwfwylRT
Call sth off (Phrasal Verb): To cancel. Sally called off the wedding because she no longer loved her fiancé. #Idiom http://t.co/Q8uJ899yAF
"Let the cat out of the bag" Example: You let the cat out of the bag when you mentioned the party tonight. It was supposed to be a surprise!
Let the cat out of the bag: To accidentally reveal a secret or surprise. #Idiom #English #ESL http://t.co/uBGVALed7T
Weekend warrior: A person who engages in a particular activity or sport only on the weekends. #Slang #Idiom #English http://t.co/iXwdLHqw2A
Hit the nail on the head: To be exactly right about something. You hit the nail on the head when you predicted rain. http://t.co/rhkG4qEC7K
Take it or leave it: A way of saying that there are no other choices; it's this or nothing. #Idiom #English #ESL RT http://t.co/gg3gDWCbeo
Grow out of (phrasal verb): Get too big for. We should go clothes shopping. Joe grew out of his jeans. #Idiom #ESL http://t.co/3Q4wp1X5YN
Hump Day: Wednesday. A reference to making it halfway through the workweek as getting "over the hump." #Idiom #ESL http://t.co/nQSKbXy0p7
Out of the gate (#idiom): At or from the very beginning. Our relationship was doomed right out of the gate. #ESL RT http://t.co/nZVeCfa48C
Smoking hot (#slang): Extremely attractive. I have a date with a smoking hot girl tonight. #Idiom #ESL #English RT me http://t.co/7nofMe34l5
To pick (sth) up (phrasal verb): To learn without trying. While traveling in Italy, she picked up a little Italian. http://t.co/P5YflTk9c8
The shit hits the fan: Serious trouble. When dad finds out you failed the exam, the shit is going to hit the fan. RT http://t.co/JXXMWu6RYy
A penny for your thoughts? (#idiom): A way of asking what someone is thinking. (Cheapskate: A stingy person) #ESL http://t.co/DpenvwQZFW
Take the piss (Brit): To make a joke; make someone look silly. #ESL #Idioms #English http://t.co/2QQ2HZli82
Take the piss (Brit): To make a joke; make someone look silly. Her friends are always taking the piss because she likes @justinbieber. #ESL
Put away (informal phrasal verb): To eat or drink easily or quickly. I'm so hungry, I could put away a whole pizza. http://t.co/fU5P8hF37S
Put away (phrasal verb): To store or save; to return something to its proper place. Please put away the dishes. #ESL http://t.co/EXKvmLnBds
Walk and chew gum (at the same time): Able to do more than one thing at a time. #Idiom #ESL #English http://t.co/xaXjNTtJQV
Case of the Mondays: Feeling bad on the first day back to work or school after the weekend. https://t.co/vYtDCdIxWD http://t.co/g05YuUsOA5
Busted (#slang): Caught; Arrested; Raided. The cops busted that shop for selling cigarettes to minors. #ESL #Idiom http://t.co/ggvSOTcLeI
Last straw: The final act or insult that calls for a response. Missing work is the last straw; we have to fire her. http://t.co/UP2E3u8ApZ
One for the books: A surprising or remarkable event. (Often used sarcastically.) That joke is one for the books. #ESL http://t.co/ly0auOlc7z
Pissed (Amer. #slang): Angry. I was really pissed when my ex-girlfriend crashed my car. #ESL #English #Idioms http://t.co/hmdKMqczM2
Pissed (Brit. #slang): Drunk. Happy Friday, Tweeters! Try not to get too pissed this weekend. #English #ESL #Idiom http://t.co/ARKS4UzCGQ
Ask (someone) out (Phrasal Verb): Invite on a date. Jim finally asked Sarah out and she said maybe. #ESL #English http://t.co/uEuK7TprK9

Wolf down: To eat quickly. We have to leave in 10 minutes, so you better wolf down your dinner. #Idioms #ESL #English http://t.co/76RIhRPEXL
Around the corner: Happening very soon. We should start planning; her birthday is just around the corner. #Idiom #ESL http://t.co/yllL2iovsd
"What's up?" (#slang) is a way of asking "What's happening?" A typical response is: "Nothing." Never say, "the sky." http://t.co/anVaTr2roY
Have a ball: To enjoy yourself immensely; have a great time. My trip to Paris was incredible; I really had a ball. http://t.co/Al2M9kuQjf
@XLBLX_LNB We use "on the fence" when we're undecided about something. I'm on the fence about quitting my job. #idiom http://t.co/uNPlkqL5iL
To be beat (#slang): Very tired; exhausted. I wish I could go to the party, but I've been working hard and I'm beat. http://t.co/RAJQVHXbl3
Speak of the devil: A reference to someone who appears unexpectedly while being talked about. #ESL #English #Idioms http://t.co/Hd862heMFm
Piece of cake: Something that is easy to do. Following Idiom Master on #Twitter is a piece of cake! #ESL #English http://t.co/J1NhALRbp2
